BSE, BOVINE - USA (WASHINGTON) (17)
***********************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail, a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 18 Mar 2004
From: Jack Herrmann (Govt Affairs) <Jack_Herrmann@govt-aff.senate.gov>

Testing for BSE at 1 in 10 million implies a 10 times more sensitive
surveillance program than testing for 1 in 1 million. But the point
is somewhat moot.
Given test sensitivity limitations, the US should be testing 2 pools
of high-risk cattle:
1) the traditional group of "high-risk" cattle that are suspect and down and
2) those cattle that are older than the feed ban (August, 1997).
It is this 2nd group that is of particular interest, because they
were actually consuming potentially BSE-contaminated meat and bone
meal, much of it imported from the EU, well into 1998.
--
J. A. Herrmann, DVM, MPH
Diplomate, American College of Theriogenologists
AVMA/AAASCongressional Science Fellow
Office of Sen. Richard J. Durbin
